    // Technology — Federal Digital Ecosystem
    'tech-fed-eyebrow': 'Federal Digital Delivery',
    'tech-fed-h3':      'Delivering Technology Within Canada\'s Digital Government Framework',
    'tech-fed-p1':      'Federal technology engagements operate inside a structured compliance environment covering the Canada Digital Ambition, Protected B cloud requirements, the Algorithmic Impact Assessment (AIA) framework, and TBS guidance on the responsible use of generative AI. Pebble Canada designs its technology delivery to be compliant with these frameworks from the outset.',
    'tech-fed-p2':      'Our team understands the approval pathways, security categorization requirements, and interoperability standards that govern technology deployment in federal environments, whether supporting a department\'s AI adoption roadmap, building analytics on approved cloud platforms, or delivering digital services against WCAG and GC design standards.',
    'tech-fed-h4a':     'Regulated AI & Algorithmic Accountability',
    'tech-fed-p3':      'The Government of Canada\'s Directive on Automated Decision-Making requires AIA completion, bias review, and explainability documentation for AI systems that affect individuals. Pebble Canada builds AIA-ready AI systems, incorporating audit trails, human-in-the-loop checkpoints, and decision-log infrastructure from day one of delivery.',
    'tech-fed-h4b':     'GC Cloud & Data Architecture',
    'tech-fed-p4':      'Federal data and analytics workloads must operate within approved cloud frameworks (Protected B, CCCS Medium) with appropriate data residency and access controls. Pebble Canada architects data platforms that meet these constraints, enabling departments to unlock AI and analytics capability without compromising their security posture or GC interoperability requirements.',
    // Workforce — Labour Market
    'wf-lm-eyebrow':    'Labour Market Position',
    'wf-lm-h3':         'Workforce Solutions for Canada\'s Tightest Labour Markets',
    'wf-lm-p1':         'Canada faces a structural workforce shortage across its highest-priority growth sectors. NRCan projects a shortfall of more than 100,000 workers in critical minerals by 2030. The defence and aerospace industrial base is constrained by an aging technical workforce. Remote and northern infrastructure projects face mobilization challenges that conventional domestic recruitment cannot address at speed.',
    'wf-lm-p2':         'Pebble Canada\'s workforce delivery model integrates domestic sourcing with structured international workforce pipelines, enabling clients to access qualified, pre-verified personnel in technical and industrial classifications where Canadian supply is chronically insufficient. Our compliance infrastructure navigates the Temporary Foreign Worker Program, labour standards obligations, and worksite safety requirements.',
    'wf-lm-h4a':        'Remote & Northern Site Deployment',
    'wf-lm-p3':         'Resource, energy, and infrastructure projects in Canada\'s remote and northern regions demand workforce pipelines that can mobilize, rotate, and sustain personnel in challenging environments, often on schedules driven by weather windows and project phasing. Pebble Canada\'s mobilization infrastructure is designed for exactly these deployments: from pre-employment credentialing through site handover.',
    'wf-lm-h4b':        'Compliance-First International Labour',
    'wf-lm-p4':         'International workforce deployment in Canada is governed by IRCC permit frameworks, ESDC labour market impact assessments, and provincial employment standards. Non-compliance creates project exposure operators cannot afford. Pebble Canada manages the full compliance chain, from LMIA documentation through to provincial onboarding obligations, as an integrated part of every deployment.',
    // Defence — Defence Industrial Base
    'def-dib-eyebrow':  'Defence Industrial Base',
    'def-dib-h3':       'Positioned Within Canada\'s Defence Procurement Ecosystem',
    'def-dib-p1':       'Canada\'s defence investment is accelerating, driven by the commitment to reach 2% GDP in NATO defence spending and a DND capital investment plan exceeding $38 billion over the coming years. The majority of this spend flows through CanadaBuys and PSPC procurement channels, within a Defence Industrial Base framework that prioritizes Canadian industrial participation, technology sovereignty, and supply chain integrity.',
    'def-dib-p2':       'Effective participation in defence procurement requires more than vendor registration. It demands familiarity with PSPC\'s contracting policy framework, compliance with the Controlled Goods Program, and the ability to produce technical bids that meet DND\'s evaluation criteria. Pebble Canada\'s procurement infrastructure is built to the standards that competitive defence solicitations require.',
    'def-dib-h4a':      'Controlled Goods & Security Compliance',
    'def-dib-p3':       'Work involving controlled technology, dual-use equipment, or sensitive programme data requires adherence to the Controlled Goods Program and, where applicable, PSPC\'s Industrial Security Programme. Pebble Canada\'s compliance posture, including our in-progress ISP registration, is designed to meet these obligations and to support clients in regulated programme environments.',
    'def-dib-h4b':      'Competitive Procurement & Bid Capability',
    'def-dib-p4':       'DND and PSPC solicitations reward suppliers who demonstrate technical depth, compliance readiness, and delivery credibility. Pebble Canada approaches competitive procurements with structured bid development: evaluation-criterion mapping, compliance matrix preparation, technical narrative, and delivery schedule documentation aligned to statement-of-work requirements.',
    // Logistics — Trade Corridor Strategy
    'log-tc-eyebrow':   'Trade Corridor Strategy',
    'log-tc-h3':        'Resilient Supply Chains Across Canada\'s Priority Trade Corridors',
    'log-tc-p1':        'Canada\'s trade strategy is shifting, diversifying dependencies and deepening engagement across the Indo-Pacific, Europe, and emerging markets. Canada\'s Indo-Pacific Strategy commits $2.3 billion to deepening Asia-Pacific economic ties, creating demand for logistics operators with established corridor presence in markets like Japan, South Korea, Australia, and Southeast Asia.',
    'log-tc-p2':        'Supply chain resilience goes beyond speed; it is about documentation discipline, customs compliance, and adaptability. Pebble Canada manages the full logistics lifecycle: freight coordination, CBSA customs clearance, CUSMA and CETA compliance, trade finance coordination through Trade Commissioner channels, and delivery verification, giving operators a single accountable partner.',
    'log-tc-h4a':       'Indo-Pacific Corridor Development',
    'log-tc-p3':        'The Indo-Pacific represents Canada\'s fastest-growing trade opportunity across critical minerals, clean technology, and advanced manufacturing. Pebble Canada\'s established presence across this corridor, from supplier relationships through to customs and last-mile delivery, enables Canadian operators to pursue Indo-Pacific procurement and export strategies with confidence, backed by infrastructure that already exists.',
    'log-tc-h4b':       'Trade Documentation & Customs Compliance',
    'log-tc-p4':        'International logistics failures are rarely about physical movement; they stem from documentation errors, misclassified goods, missed permit requirements, or customs delays that cascade into project timelines. Pebble Canada\'s trade compliance capability, covering import/export documentation, tariff classification, permits, and origin certification under CUSMA and CETA, is integrated into every shipment.',

